Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=20
Happy Monday! This is my shortest piece in a long time =E2=80=94 it all fit=
s in the email =E2=80=94 on a topic that=E2=80=99s near and dear to my hear=
t: the real and growing power of writing down the future you want to see ex=
ist.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
The Enchanted Notebook
Imagine that, sitting at your desk on a normal Monday, a Monday just like t=
oday, a wizard pops into your office and hands you an enchanted notebook.=
=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWrite any idea in this notebook,=E2=80=9D the wizard whispers, =E2=
=80=9Cand it will show you how to make it real.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The notebook is fantasy, but one very real way to create the future is to i=
magine what it looks like, write it down, and then work backwards.=C2=A0
On Thursday, I was walking through Soho and life was good. I=E2=80=99d just=
 grabbed coffee with one of my favorite entrepreneurs, the sun was shining =
after a morning shower, I had a box full of Little Cupcake Bakeshop cupcake=
s for Dev in hand, and I was listening to Lex Fridman interview Ray Kurzwei=
l.=C2=A0
Kurzweil wrote one of the first books that got me really interested in tech=
nology, The Singularity is Near [ https://substack.com/redirect/fefcc699-ac=
f4-4396-b705-e8d2f586b19b?r=3D9p0gt ]. Way back in 2005, my friend Nick, th=
e same one who listened to Spotify on the party bus with me [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/4e043f6c-9e43-4d69-8a68-c1ff593de7ee?r=3D9p0gt ], told me =
I had to read it. And he was right. It blew my mind open.=C2=A0
The whole interview was fascinating =E2=80=93 Kurzweil=E2=80=99s brand of h=
yper-optimistic futurism is catnip to me. His superpower is believing harde=
r than anyone else in the power of exponential curves.=C2=A0
His 2001 essay, The Law of Accelerating Returns [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/3d6fd064-c9c4-4ddd-95aa-9982b405b3c5?r=3D9p0gt ], is worth a read both=
 for the ideas themselves and for how well many of his 21-year-old predicti=
ons have held up. In it, for example, he calls the timing of the paradigm s=
hift in computing=E2=80=99s exponential growth (the shift from CPUs to GPUs=
, from Moore=E2=80=99s Law to Huang=E2=80=99s Law) in the 2010s, and the pr=
ecipitous declines in the cost of human genome sequencing.
Those ideas, and the idea of the Singularity, were so ahead of their time a=
nd out there that they=E2=80=99ve invited criticism from a host of Very Sma=
rt People. On the one side are experts, who understand the day-to-day diffi=
culties of actually making Kurzweil=E2=80=99s predictions come true; on the=
 other is Kurzweil, who looks at the curves and trusts that they=E2=80=99ll=
 continue.=C2=A0
Time will tell which side is right, and he=E2=80=99s missed on some predict=
ions in the interim.  But in the conversation with Fridman, Kurzweil makes =
a compelling argument that the consensus view on the timeline for artificia=
l intelligence is coming back around to the timeline that he put forth in 1=
999, and has held to since: pass the Turing Test in 2029, Singularity in 20=
45. If Kurzweil is right, or even close to right, he may go down as the per=
son with the greatest ability to predict the future in human history.=C2=A0
So when Fridman asked Kurzweil about how he comes up with his ideas, I stop=
ped walking, paused, rewound, and focused.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s the video, starting at the relevant point:
I transcribed the key part here:
Fridman: You=E2=80=99ve talked about how you use lucid dreaming to think, t=
o come up with ideas as a source of creativity. Can you maybe talk through =
that? You=E2=80=99ve invented a lot of things. You=E2=80=99ve come up with =
and thought through some very interesting ideas. What advice would you give=
, or can you speak to the process of thinking, how to think creatively?
Kurzweil: Sometimes I will think through in a dream and try to interpret th=
at, but I think the key issue that I would tell younger people is to put yo=
urself in the position that what you=E2=80=99re trying to create already ex=
ists. And then you=E2=80=99re explaining=E2=80=A6
Fridman: =E2=80=A6how it works?
Kurzweil: Exactly.
Fridman: That=E2=80=99s really interesting. You paint a world that you woul=
d like to exist, you think can exist, and reverse engineer that.
Kurzweil: And then you actually imagine you=E2=80=99re giving a speech abou=
t how you created this. Well you=E2=80=99d have to then work backwards abou=
t how you created it to make it work.
Fridman: That=E2=80=99s brilliant, and that requires some imagination, too,=
 some first principles thinking. You need to visualize that world. That=E2=
=80=99s really interesting.
Kurzweil: And generally when I talk about things that we=E2=80=99re trying =
to invent, I would use the present tense as if it already exists. Not just =
to give myself that confidence, but everybody else that=E2=80=99s working o=
n it. We just have to do all of the steps to make it actual.
The way Kurzweil describes it, innovation is half storytelling. It=E2=80=99=
s our Enchanted Notebook, just with humans filling in the enchanted bits fo=
r now.=20
Write a speech, or a story, about the thing you want to create or the futur=
e world you want to inhabit. Paint that world in detail so rich, using the =
present tense, that it feels like you already live there. Imagine the magic=
al technology [ https://substack.com/redirect/4e043f6c-9e43-4d69-8a68-c1ff5=
93de7ee?r=3D9p0gt ] that has become so ordinary that people just use it eve=
ry day without a second thought. How do people behave in this world? What=
=E2=80=99s changed about them? What=E2=80=99s stayed the same?
Then, reverse engineer it. What components go into that technology? When wi=
ll which pieces be technically feasible? What machines need to exist to man=
ufacture the technology? Where did you need to work with regulators to make=
 sure people were allowed to use it? What will the unit economics look like=
? Which cost curves had to keep falling exponentially for those unit econom=
ics to make sense? How did they improve with scale, and which distribution =
channels did you use to sell the product?=C2=A0
Kurzweil=E2=80=99s process is reminiscent of Amazon=E2=80=99s Future Press =
Release [ https://substack.com/redirect/9f608626-effd-48c7-bcb5-b2307ba8ab4=
e?r=3D9p0gt ]. When teams at Amazon proposed a new product, Jeff Bezos made=
 them write a press release from the perspective of specific time in the fu=
ture at which the product has been released and goals have been accomplishe=
d. Former Amazon exec John Rossman laid out the four rules for future press=
 releases [ https://substack.com/redirect/9f608626-effd-48c7-bcb5-b2307ba8a=
b4e?r=3D9p0gt ]:
Rule 1. The goal must be stated at a future point in time at which success =
has been achieved and realized.=C2=A0
Rule 2. Start with the customer.=C2=A0
Rule 3. Set an audacious and clear goal.=C2=A0
Rule 4. Outline the principles used that led to success.=C2=A0
In either case, Amazonian or Kurzweilian, the process of bringing a new thi=
ng to life requires a combination of dreams and details, in three parts:
Imagine a future world and write it down.=C2=A0
Fill in all of the details with as much technical and research-based suppor=
t as possible.=C2=A0
Execute on those details to make the thing real.
When I heard Kurzweil describe his process, I went through three emotional =
states:
Excitement: Writing! That=E2=80=99s what I do!=C2=A0
Depression: Oh=E2=80=A6 I=E2=80=99m not technical. I wouldn=E2=80=99t know =
how to reverse engineer something.
Wonder: Wait=E2=80=A6 how long is reverse engineering going to require actu=
al engineering knowledge?
I wonder how far off we are from the Enchanted Notebook: the point at which=
 technology eliminates, or dramatically shrinks, the gap between imaginatio=
n and reverse engineering. And from there, how much further we are from the=
 point at which technology eliminates, or dramatically shrinks, the gap bet=
ween reverse engineering and execution.=C2=A0
One way to think about the Singularity is the point at which human-computer=
 combinations do all three steps, pretty much in real-time, and carry out t=
he execution with nanobots or something. But far before that point, it seem=
s like we should be able to dream up those products, write them down, and l=
et AI do the reverse engineering.=C2=A0
Last week, Replit CEO Amjad Masad tweeted something to that effect:=C2=A0
Caveats abound. Replit=E2=80=99s GhostWriter is still in beta and only help=
s humans write code. It can=E2=80=99t turn problem into product on its own =
yet, and that seems like a big bridge to cross. Plus, software engineering =
is likely an easier problem for AI to solve from a text input than mechanic=
al engineering, if only because the amount of public code available to lear=
n on is much larger than the amount of public CADs available, especially fo=
r sufficiently advanced designs, and is likely easier for AI to make sense =
of. And AI-assisted coding isn=E2=80=99t solving the kind of novel problems=
 that AI-assisted physical product innovation would need to solve to be rea=
lly magical. And and, there are likely a thousand things that I=E2=80=99m n=
ot thinking of here that make this harder than it seems to a non-technical,=
 optimistically-minded person like me.=C2=A0
BUT it seems almost certain that we=E2=80=99ll reach a point in the coming =
decades at which I=E2=80=99ll be able to write, =E2=80=9CSingle-person spac=
ecraft capable of launching 500 pounds into orbit and sustaining life for u=
p to six months=E2=80=9D or whatever and get back a reverse-engineered CAD =
file, instruction set, and materials list with prices and suppliers. If the=
 idea isn=E2=80=99t feasible yet, it might return a list of bottlenecks wit=
h best-guesses for when they=E2=80=99ll be solved, and all of those bottlen=
eck lists might serve as a smorgasbord for researchers and entrepreneurs lo=
oking for big problems to solve.=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0
All of this seems infeasible and outlandish in the present. This current wa=
ve of AI innovation is creating a hype cycle, as every exciting technology =
does, and the reality likely won=E2=80=99t live up to the hype for a little=
 while:=C2=A0
Michael Dempsey thinks we=E2=80=99re in the Curiosity Phase [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/b2ecbc20-f00f-4ea6-99e4-cbf141d5397a?r=3D9p0gt ], past the=
 Peak of Inflated Expectations and Trough of Disillusionment, exciting enou=
gh to lure people in while still being a really difficult spot in which to =
build an AI-powered company.=C2=A0
But let me dream for a minute. It is moving really fast.=C2=A0
Last Monday, I wrote =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re one small leap =E2=80=93 some e=
nterprising young coder hooking Stable Diffusion up to a voice input =E2=80=
=93 from being able to speak words to conjure magic, incantation brought to=
 reality.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
On Wednesday, two days later, OpenAI released and open sourced Whisper, whi=
ch will make it easier to make incantation real.
Friday morning, I spent time manually transcribing that Lex Fridman - Ray K=
urzweil exchange.
Friday afternoon, @jeffistyping dropped Youtube Whisperer [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/a43686da-036b-4860-8bb1-94d55dbcdb3f?r=3D9p0gt ], which uses=
 Whisper to create transcripts from YouTube videos with Hugging Face [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/ae1d4543-1427-4b3c-a69b-88bd5f75c66a?r=3D9p0gt ].
I know that I didn=E2=80=99t write those things into reality, but it certai=
nly felt like it.=C2=A0
Kurzweil has an explanation for the hype cycle, too. In The Law of Accelera=
ting Returns [ https://substack.com/redirect/3d6fd064-c9c4-4ddd-95aa-9982b4=
05b3c5?r=3D9p0gt ], he pointed out that exponential curves feel linear and =
flattish in the moment, until they don=E2=80=99t:=C2=A0
Most technology forecasts ignore altogether this =E2=80=9Chistorical expone=
ntial view=E2=80=9D of technological progress. That is why people tend to o=
verestimate what can be achieved in the short term (because we tend to leav=
e out necessary details), but underestimate what can be achieved in the lon=
g term (because the exponential growth is ignored).
Another way to view the Singularity is the point at which the short-term/lo=
ng-term mismatch disappears, because the gap between idea and execution dis=
appears.=C2=A0
Whether the Singularity is near or not, it seems useful to try to shrink th=
e mismatch by dreaming big about the future but making sure to fill in the =
necessary details. Very few people are great storytellers and great enginee=
rs, but AI might be able to help each side get better at the other.=C2=A0
Engineers can run the details through GPT-3 and get a story.=C2=A0
Storytellers can write the story into RevEng-4 (or whatever OpenAI calls it=
) and get the reverse-engineered details.=C2=A0
Dreams and reality will move ever closer to each other.=C2=A0
Whether that future is two months, two years, or two decades away, or wheth=
er it never comes, a good proximate next step on any timeline is for more p=
eople to paint rich, detailed visions of the future that they want to see c=
ome true.
Imagination isn=E2=80=99t sufficient for creating the future, for now, but =
it is necessary.=20
Thanks to Dan and Puja for editing, and to Secureframe [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/73ce8242-25e1-4160-ab52-8054de0b8c47?r=3D9p0gt ] for supporting=
 Not Boring!=20
We=E2=80=99ll be back to you on Thursday with a Deep Dive on one of the mos=
t sneaky successful startups out there. Until then, have a great week!=20
Thanks for reading,
Packy

